as cast aside the stabilisers and come of age as a cycling nation. Back-to-back Tour wins and a clattering jackpot of Olympic gold have raised the sport's domestic profile to giddying heights, so it's perhaps no surprise that the official build-up to July's <em>grand départ</em> begins today, a full 100 days before the pros roll out of Leeds. What are more arresting are the scale and spread of <a href=\"http://festival.yorkshire.com/\" title=\"\">the Yorkshire festival's 47 themed events</a>, which suggest that Britain's cycling renaissance goes deeper than a 15% post-Olympic jump in bike sales. We've wobbled out of Halfords and are pedalling into our previously uncharted cultural hinterland.</p><p>Some events tick the expected boxes. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2014/jan/29/maxine-peake-yorkshire-cyclist-play-stage-tour-de-france\" title=\"\">Actor Maxine Peake's debut play Beryl</a> – based on the extraordinary career of Leeds-born cycling legend Beryl Burton, winner of seven world titles – will be performed live for the first time. Meanwhile, giant grass-based art installations will line a section of the Tour route, as a tribute to the hay-bale sculptures seen in all those Tour de France helicopter shots. And there's an exhibition of Tour photography from the 1960s to the present, as well as open-air film screenings.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-433070334'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/26/1395853218657/Ghost-Peloton-008.jpg' alt='Ghost Peloton' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Ghost Peloton.</figcaption></figure><p>But the headline act is <a href=\"http://www.cineyorkshire.co.uk/film_detail.php?ID=1413\" title=\"\">Velorama, Daisy Asquith's festival-commissioned mashup of bike-themed newsreels, short films and home movies</a>. On one level, it's a simple, nostalgic celebration of the sit-up-and-beg's monochrome heyday, a tribute to the earnest utilitarianism of Britain's cycling heritage, when the nation whistled off to work with trousers tucked into socks, or puffed home from weekend rides with red cheeks and black fingers.</p><p>But Velorama also explores the meatier profundities of life in the saddle. \"The cyclist is master of his own fate,\" intones the newsreel announcer, as boys with Brylcreem side partings stand portentously astride their first bikes, at the threshold of adult independence. As Asquith's archive clips remind us, the bicycle pushed back all manner of literal and metaphorical horizons. The sort of activities once restricted to the bikeshed could now be savoured in rural seclusion. So too those existential ponderings that spring reflexively from the loneliness of the long-distance cyclist.</p><p>A bookseller told me recently that cycling books now outsell works about any other sport. This must partly be down to its everyman appeal: though not everyone can do 100 keepy-uppies, we all know what it is to grind up a hill then freewheel madly down the other side. And those ruminative hours in the saddle are more deeply inspirational than a kickabout in the park, with the professional road-race version of the sport serving up a uniquely tempting smorgasbord of dramatic themes: heroism, loyalty, betrayal and weapons-grade cheating, all washed down with lashings of blood, sweat and tears.</p><p>Clearly, there's a lot to say about cycling – and the Yorkshire festival says more of it than you might think. Breaking free from the peloton of predictability is Luce, Belgian theatre company Tol's drama inspired by the rivalry between Italian cycling legends Fausto Coppi and Gino Bartali; its actors will be suspended throughout from wires slung high above the audience. Meanwhile, a 50-strong, LED-illuminated \"ghost peloton\" is to stage a choreographed night tour of Leeds. And – marching straight to the surrealist high ground – the villagers of Bentham plan to mark <em>le grand départ</em> by covering their cars in turf and decorating fields with giant cycling sheep and \"sculptural underwear\".</p><p>Only a little less strange is PianoPorté, Cragg Vale's nod to the Tour's superhuman struggle against gravity: a team of cyclists will pull a grand piano six miles up the longest continuous ascent in England, on a platform designed by <a href=\"http://www.andyplant.co.uk/\" title=\"\">sculptor Andy Plant</a>. As the ensemble inches upwards, local pianists are to play a specially commissioned musical cycle.</p><p>This is exactly the sort of high-concept experience that continental creatives were dabbling with back at the dawn of the cycling age. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2010/oct/14/top-10-cycling-novels\" title=\"\">Albert Jarry's dystopian novel The Supermale</a>, published two years before the first Tour, described a 10,000-mile race between teams of riders literally bolted to five-man bikes (their \"external skeletons\"), and fuelled with a generally fatal cocktail of alcohol and strychnine known as \"perpetual motion food\". Jarry appears to have been a gigantically slappable Pete Doherty-style pain in the arse, a man who referred to himself in the royal plural, insisted on calling his own bicycle \"that which rolls\", and once expressed his love of absinthe by riding through Paris painted green, firing two revolvers in the air.</p><p>However, unlike Doherty, Jarry was a true visionary: beyond the artistic hyperbole, his dreadful forecast of cycling's competitive future proved compellingly prescient. \"In the ideal bicycle race,\" wrote <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2001/jul/02/cycling.cycling\" title=\"\">the Tour's merciless founder, Henri Desgrange</a>, \"there would be only one finisher.\" The 1914 Giro d'Italia, which I retraced last year on a wooden-wheeled 1914 bike, came closest to realising this awful vision: of 81 starters in this tour of Italy, only eight were able to finish. One rider gamely tried to continue after losing an eye; and the solitary British entrant, double Olympic medallist Freddie Grubb, was so traumatised by the unfolding horrors that he retired on the first day and never rode again.</p><p>We can perhaps forgive ourselves for being 100 years late in appreciating the artistic potential of cyclo-suffering as an allegory for the human condition. Britain isn't big enough, or steep enough, to have hosted an attritional epic along the lines of the Tour or the Giro. We don't have blizzards or merciless broiling sun. It's tough to work up drizzle and a sore bottom into some transcendental Calvary of Sisyphean toil, and the sardonic understatement hardwired into our national psyche would, in any case, resist such overblown musings.</p><p>Compare and contrast Bradley Wiggins' victory address with that of Maurice Garin, winner of the inaugural 1903 Tour. Garin told the gathered throng: \"I see myself, from the start of the race, like a bull pierced by the toreador's spears, dragging them along every metre of the way, never able to cast off the torment.\" Handed the microphone as he stood on the Tour podium, Wiggins told the crowd: \"We're just going to call the raffle numbers now.\"</p><p>Garin's description seemed vividly reminiscent of the infernal, endless, hamster-wheel torture foretold by Jarry, though he was at least spared the fate of Jarry's fictional winner. There are still 100 days for some avant-garde Yorkshire art collective to recreate his novel's podium ceremony – in which the triumphant \"supermale\" is shackled to an electric love machine and literally shagged to death.• Gironimo!, Tim Moore's account of his ride round the 1914 Giro d'Italia route, is published on 1 May. Festival details: festival.yorkshire.com.</p>","headline":"Blazing saddles: how Yorkshire will kick off the Tour de France","trailText":"<p>As Yorkshire begins its Tour de France festival, <strong>Tim Moore</strong> freewheels through a brief history of British pedal power – from Brylcreemed boys to the loneliness of the long