t the departure in London we never saw as many people as we did in those two days. Here's going to be exactly the same.\"</p><p>And he reckons Froome is \"No1 favourite\" to repeat his triumph in last year's Tour. But he said Froome and 2012 winner Sir Bradley are not the only Brits who should be talked about.</p><p>\"It's not just a question of those two people,\" said. \"Now in Britain cycling is completely opening out. It's all over the country. This is going to lead to more success in cycling.\"</p><p>Hinault said: \"It difficult to say because in '12 it was Wiggins, in '13 it was Froome. It's difficult to say what's going to happen this year. We mustn't forget about [Mark] Cavendish, though, because he's also in the running.\"</p><p>Cavendish is likely to be the main focus of the opening day of the Tour as he is expected to do well in the relatively flat stage and the finish is in Harrogate, where his mother lives.</p><p>Yorkshire-based pro-cyclist Dean Downing, who was riding with Hinault, said: \"It would mean everything to Mark Cavendish. His sole goal for the start of the year is that stage. That's his first goal of the year which is 100 days away.</p><p>\"It would be pretty special for Yorkshire but when Mark Cavendish puts his mind to something he tells everybody what he's going to do and he generally gets it done. For him, personally, it would be great, for his family, but for Yorkshire as well.\"</p><p>Downing said some continental Tour contenders will be panicking about stage two, which includes a range of difficult climbs. He said the last 25 miles (40k) into Sheffield was \"pretty brutal\".</p><p>\"In the next 100 days you might see a lots of the pro-teams, the Tour contenders, coming over with their teams to recon [reconnoitre] this stage two route,\" he said. \"It'll be a great finish and a great spectacle for, hopefully, the tens of thousands of people who are going to come out and watch it.\"</p><p>His brother Russ, also a pro rider, said: \"Some guys will know Holme Moss from previous races but the rest of the climbs they won't know. To be honest, myself and Dean did the last 40k the other week and we were surprised how tough it was.\"</p>","headline":"Tour de France will be 'big party' for Yorkshire, says Bernard Hinault","trailText":"The five-times winner said even the French are getting excited about the Tour's return to the UK","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/26/1395858908612/Bernard-Hinault-rides-up--006.jpg","wordcount":"641","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-03-29T18:38:01Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/mar/26/tour-de-france-big-party-yorkshire-bernard-hinault","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/2014/mar/26/tour-de-france-big-party-yorkshire-bernard-hinault","tags":[{"id":"sport/tour-de-france-2014","webTitle":"Tour de France 2014","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/tour-de-france-2014","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/tour-de-france-2014","references":[]},{"id":"sport/tourdefrance","webTitle":"Tour de France","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/tourdefrance","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/tourdefrance","references":[]},{"id":"sport/cycling","webTitle":"Cycling","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/cycling","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/cycling","references":[]},{"id":"sport/sport","webTitle":"Sport","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/sport","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/sport","references":[]},{"id":"tone/news","webTitle":"News","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/news","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/tone/news","refer