n the race left Milan. However, the Briton, who won in 2009, started his sprint slightly too early and ran out of gas in the final metres, fading to fifth. The hot favourite Peter Sagan of Slovakia, who has yet to win a major classic race, never had a chance to attack and finished a disappointing 10th. Poland's Michal Kwiatkowski, one of the in-form riders early in the season, abandoned with about 50km remaining.</p><p>Rainy conditions had trimmed the peloton to some 60 riders at the foot of the Cipressa climb but neither Cancellara nor Sagan's teams were able to shake off the sprinters.</p><p>The Giro champion Vincenzo Nibali attacked in that climb despite the high pace set at the front of the peloton by Sagan's Cannondale team, but the Italian was reined in near the top of the Poggio, the last ascent of the day.</p><p>Several riders tried their luck solo, but after nearly 300km of racing nobody had the energy  to beat the pack.</p>","headline":"Milan-San Remo: Team Sky's Ben Swift is third behind Alexander Kristoff","trailText":"Team Sky's Ben Swift claimed a surprise third-placed finish in the first of the season's five Monument one-day races","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Sport/Pix/columnists/2014/3/23/1395596087973/Ben-Swift-006.jpg","wordcount":"348","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-03-26T17:37:58Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/mar/23/milan-san-remo-ben-swift-alexander-kristoff","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/2014/mar/23/milan-san-remo-ben-swift-alexander-kristoff","tags":[{"id":"sport/cycling","webTitle":"Cycling","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/cycling","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/cycling","references":[]},{"id":"sport/team-sky","webTitle":"Team Sky","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/team-sky","apiUrl":"http://beta.conte