</p><p>According to Sky, Henao returned to his home in Colombia last October and underwent out-of-competition tests. \"We need to understand these readings better. We want to do the right thing and we want to be fair. It's important not to jump to conclusions.\"</p><p>A Team Sky spokesman explained that the team has an internal panel, from both inside and outside the team, which examines the riders' data from external tests as part of their compliance process, and it is this system that has raised the questions over Henao.</p><p>On their website, Sky added that after last month's Tour of Oman, where he finished seventh, they contacted the UCI and Cycling Anti-Doping Foundation – the arm's length body which monitors anti-doping for the UCI – to see if it could offer any insights.</p><p>The UCI said it supported the move. \"As a matter of principle we are supportive of teams pursuing a policy of closely monitoring their athletes,\" a UCI spokesperson said. \"This is something that has been monitored by the team. This is their own programme and that's very important.\"</p><p>Brailsford added that the investigation into Henao will focus on the fact that he lives and trains at altitude, in common with many of the other Colombian cyclists in the professional peloton. His home at Rionegro, close to Medellin, is at 7,000 feet above sea level.</p><p>The performance-enhancing effects of taking riders to altitude are well known to Sky: training camps at altitude on Mount Teide in Tenerife formed a key part of both Bradley Wiggins' and Chris Froome's buildup to their Tour de France victories. What is less clear, the team feel, is the way those cyclists who are high-altitude \"natives\" function, which is why they are biding their time over Henao.</p><p>\"Sergio was raised in the mountains, goes back in winter and lives and trains at different levels,\" said Brailsford. \"We've looked as far as we can at the effects of this. Our understanding is limited by a lack of scientific research into 'altitude natives' such as Sergio. We are commissioning independent scientific research to better understand the effects of prolonged periods at altitude after returning from sea level, specifically on altitude natives.\"</p><p>Henao is expected to be out of commission for eight weeks, which means that he may still be available to start the Tour de France in July. He was expected to race the Dauphiné Libéré stage race in June and then possibly to make his debut in the Tour in support of Froome's title defence.</p>","headline":"Team Sky drop rider due to 'questions' over results of anti-doping tests","trailText":"<p>Team Sky have taken rider Sergio Henao off their race schedule due to \"questions\" overs the Colombian's results in out-of-competition, anti-doping tests</p>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Sport/Pix/pictures/2014/3/19/1395229591934/Sergio-Henao-004.jpg","wordcount":"583","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-03-22T09:53:20Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/mar/19/team-sky-sergio-henao-anti-doping","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/2014/mar/19/team-sky-sergio-henao-anti-doping","tags":[{"id":"sport/team-sky","webTitle":"Team Sky","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/team-sky","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/team-sky","references":[]},{"id":"sport/cycling","webTitle":"Cycling","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/cycling","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/cycling","references":[]},{"id":"sport/sport","webTitle":"Sport","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/sport","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/sport","references":[]},{"id":"tone/news","webTitle":"News","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/news","apiUrl":"ht